\begin_layout Section
The Polarized Target System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Polarized target was widely used to extract the polarized neutron and proton
 data in order to study the nucleon structure in the spin degree of freedom
 in nuclear and particle experiments.
 There are several types of polarized target system used in Jefferson Lab.
 The polarized ammonia (
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{3}$
\end_inset

) target is used to study the spin of proton, while the polarized 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 target acts as an neutron target.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polarized 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{3}$
\end_inset

 target
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polarized proton target used during the g2p experiment is from UVa target
 group, which uses solid ammonia as the proton material.
 It has been used for many experiments before, like SANE, RSS in Hall C
 and EG1-4 in Hall B at Jefferson Lab, and E143, E155, E155x in SLAC.
 The dynamic nuclear polarization (DNP) method is used to polarize the target,
 which is using low temperature down to 1 K and 140 GHz microwave to pump
 the polarization into a high level up to 94 %.
 The nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is used for measuring the polarization,
 while the thermal equilibrium (TE) polarization is used for calibrating
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polarization mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Dynamic Nuclear Polarization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamic nuclear polarization (DNP) was used to achieve high polarization
 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{3}$
\end_inset

 target.
 A microwave generator emits the microwaves at the splitting energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{NMR}$
\end_inset

.
 The energy splitting between two electron sublevel 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{e}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{e}=-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 is about 140 GHz at 5 T and 70 GHz at 2.5 T, and the energy splitting between
 two proton sublevels 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{P}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 is about 200 MHz at 5T.
 Thanks for the granular control of the microwave technology, we can obtain
 any frequency we want use in microwave section accurately by using the
 cavity.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 polarization from the state of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{-\frac{1}{2}}p_{-\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\frac{1}{2}}p_{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 needs 140.2 GHz microwave and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 polarization from the state of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\frac{1}{2}}p_{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{-\frac{1}{2}}p_{-\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 needs 140.5 GHz microwave for the 5T magnet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Thermal Equilibrium (TE) Polarization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Zeeman splitting because of the high magnet field causes 2 sublevels which
 the proton's spin is 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The population of these two sublevels is calculated by the Boltzmann law:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{\frac{1}{2}}=N_{-\frac{1}{2}}e^{-\frac{\Delta E}{k_{B}T}},\label{eq:te}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{-\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 are the population of two sublevels, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the environment, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzmann constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 is the energy difference of two sublevels in the magnetic field of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 As defined polarization by 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\frac{1}{2})=\frac{N_{\frac{1}{2}}-N_{-\frac{1}{2}}}{N_{\frac{1}{2}}+N_{-\frac{1}{2}}}$
\end_inset

, the thermal equilibrium polarization is calculated as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\frac{1}{2})=tanh(\frac{\mu B}{k_{B}T})\label{eq:teP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is only the function of magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 The proton's thermal polarization is about 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\%$
\end_inset

 at 5 T magnet field and 1 K temperature.
 It is used for calibrating the NMR measurement.
\end_layout

