\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The technique of adiabatic Fast Passage (AFP) is the key method in NMR Sweep.
 The NMR signal is received with NMR pick-up coils when the spin reversal
 happened since the holding field or frequency sweeping across resonance.
 Combining with the same measurement performed for a water sample, the polarizat
ion of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 is obtained.
 Both the field sweep and the frequency sweep are used for the NMR measurement.
 The NMR field sweep is described as follows.
 The frequency sweep has similar principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classically, a torque is exerted by the magnetic field if a 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 nucleus is in a static magnetic field:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d\vec{M}}{dt} & =\gamma\vec{M}\times\vec{H_{0}},\label{eq:1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{M}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 nucleus magnetic moment,
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is the holding field, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the gyromagnetic ratio.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\vec{M}}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is written in rotating frame as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d\vec{M}}{dt} & =\frac{\partial\vec{M}}{\partial t}+\vec{\omega}\times\vec{M},\label{eq:2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is the frequency of the rotating frame.
 Combining (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

) with (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

), the following formula is obtained:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\vec{M}}{\partial t} & =\gamma\vec{M}\times(\vec{H_{0}}+\frac{\vec{\omega}}{\gamma}).\label{eq:3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we make comparisons about (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"

\end_inset

), the holding field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{0}}$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

) has been changed as effective field 
\begin_inset Formula $(\vec{H_{0}}+\frac{\vec{\omega}}{\gamma})$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"

\end_inset

).
 We can choose a rotating frame that make the effective field vanished,
 i.e.
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=-\gamma H_{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 The holding field is in z direction in all time, and we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{0}}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}\vec{e_{z}}$
\end_inset

.
 In x direction a RF field of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H}_{RF}=2H_{1}cos(\omega t)\vec{e_{z}}=H_{1}\hat{e}_{+}^{'}+H_{1}\hat{e}_{\_}^{'}$
\end_inset

 is applied, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}_{\pm}^{'}=cos(\omega t)\hat{e}_{x}\pm sin(\omega t)\hat{e}_{y}$
\end_inset

 which only needs one of them.
 In the rotating frame the effective field can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vec{H_{e}} & =(H_{0}+\frac{\omega}{\gamma})\vec{e_{z}}+H_{1}\hat{e}_{+}^{'},\label{eq:4}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}\vec{i}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and have a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 to rotate it.
 The absolute value, i.e.
 the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{e}}$
\end_inset

 is written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{e} & =\sqrt{(H_{0}+\frac{\omega}{\gamma})^{2}+H_{1}^{2}}.\label{eq:5}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 between the holding field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and effective field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{H_{e}}$
\end_inset

 can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
tan\theta=\frac{H_{1}}{H_{0}+\frac{\omega}{\gamma}} & =\frac{\omega_{1}}{\omega_{0}-\omega}\label{eq:6}
\end{align}

\end_inset

As the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is much smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

, the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 can be regarded as 0 unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}-\omega$
\end_inset

 close to 0.
 Once the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 is passed to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, the nuclear magnetic resonance could be happened and the magnetic moment
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 becomes anti-parallel to the holding field by following the effective field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 average magnetic moment 
\begin_inset Formula $<\vec{M}>$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the signal height.
 Because the polarization of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $<\vec{M}>$
\end_inset

, the relationship between signal height and polarization is obtained by
 taking the calibration process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The water calibration is used to calibrate the NMR signal by measuring the
 thermal polarization of the proton in water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Electron paramagnetic resonance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 nucleus are polarized, a small magnet field at a level of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.1\,Gauss$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "XiaochaoZheng"

\end_inset

 was generated by their spins.
 In addition to the holding magnet field of 
\begin_inset Formula $25\,Gauss$
\end_inset

, the EPR frequency is decomposed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{EPR}=\nu_{0}\pm\Delta\nu_{EPR},\label{eq:nuepr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 is caused by holding field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{EPR}$
\end_inset

 is related to the polarization of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the direction of polarization.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{EPR}$
\end_inset

 is much smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

, the adiabatic fast passage (AFP) sweep 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "abagrambook"

\end_inset

 was taken to reverse the polarization of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 periodically.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{EPR}$
\end_inset

 is extracted from the EPR frequency calculated before and after spin reversal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\nu_{EPR}=\frac{\nu_{EPR,\uparrow\Uparrow}-\nu_{EPR,\downarrow\Uparrow}}{2},\label{eq:deltanuepr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\uparrow$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\downarrow$
\end_inset

 are two spin directions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

 nucleus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Uparrow$
\end_inset

 are the direction of holding field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{He}$
\end_inset

 has the following relation with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{EPR}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevA.71.013414"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{He}=\frac{3}{8\pi}\frac{(2I+1)}{g_{s}\mu_{B}}\frac{h}{\mu_{K}}\frac{\Delta\nu_{EPR}}{(1+\epsilon)\kappa_{0}\rho_{He}},\label{eq:polvsnu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the electron 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 is Bohr magneton, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the nuclear spin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mu_{K}}{h}$
\end_inset

 is the magnetic moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the magnetic moment correction factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the frequency shift enhancement factor depending on temperature
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kelleher,PhysRevA.58.3004"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{He}$
\end_inset

 is the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}He$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Frequency lock
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frequency modulation (FM) sweep is used to find the EPR resonance frequency
 in order to lock it to do the AFP sweep.
 If a magnetic field with EPR resonance frequency is added, two splitted
 states between 
\begin_inset Formula $5P_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $5P_{3/2}$
\end_inset

 are mixed.
 More electrons in state of 
\begin_inset Formula $5P_{3/2}$
\end_inset

 causes decay from 
\begin_inset Formula $5P_{3/2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $5S_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and emit 785nm light which called 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 light.
 In the meantime the 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 absorption spectrum happens caused by 
\begin_inset Formula $5S_{1/2}\:\rightarrow\,5P_{1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Because of the narrow laser we used, the laser light absorbed cleanly with
 little noise of background, which means we can get a clean 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 absorption spectrum.
 The original gaussian peak of 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 light is almost absorbed.
 Either 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 light could be used to lock the EPR resonance frequency.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 light are picked by photodiode and exported by fiber.
 In order to get maximum signal, the best place was found for photodiode.
 The photodiode for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 was placed in the top of the oven, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 was placed in the front of the oven.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 filter was used for the 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 photodiode to detect the increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 light.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 light is much brighter than 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

, no filter was added for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 photodiode.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Frequency-modulation-sweep"

\end_inset

 shows an example of EPR FM sweep by either using 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

